===Documentary===
[[File:Man with a movie camera 1929 2.png|thumb|''[[Man with a Movie Camera]]'' (1929) topped 2014 Sight & Sound poll of experts.]]

* ''[[Man with a Movie Camera]]'' (1929) was voted the greatest documentary of all time with 125 votes (100 critics and 25 filmmakers) in a [[Sight & Sound#Greatest Documentaries of All Time|2014 Sight & Sound poll]] of 238 critics, curators, and academics (including many documentary specialists) and 103 filmmakers.<ref>
* {{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sight-sound-magazine/greatest-docs |title=Critics' 50 Greatest Documentaries of All Time|publisher=BFI |accessdate=27 February 2015}}
* {{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sight-sound-magazine/greatest-docs-full-poll|title=The Greatest Documentaries of All Time – all the votes|publisher=BFI|accessdate=17 January 2017}}
* {{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/polls-surveys/documentary-poll-acknowledgements|title=The Sight & Sound Documentary Poll: acknowledgements|publisher=BFI|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
* ''[[Hoop Dreams]]'' (1994) was ranked as the greatest documentary of all time by the [[International Documentary Association]] (IDA) in 2007. Voters selected from a list of over 700 films.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.documentary.org/content/top-25-docs|title=IDA's Top 25 Documentaries|newspaper=International Documentary Association|access-date=28 November 2016}}</ref>
* ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'' (2002) heads the list of 20 all-time favorite non-fiction films selected by members of the IDA in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/library/weekly/aabowlingawardnews.htm|title="Bowling for Columbine" Named Best Documentary Film|date=12 December 2002|publisher=About.com|accessdate=18 September 2009}}</ref>

