* ''[[Persona (film)|Persona]]'' (1966) reached the highest position (number 5 in 1972) of any Swedish film on any of ''Sight & Sound''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s lists of greatest films of all time.<ref name="S&S" />

===Taiwan===
{{See also|Cinema of Taiwan}}
* ''[[A City of Sadness]]'' ({{lang|zh-hant|悲情城市}}; 1989) was voted the best Chinese-language film of all time with 73 votes in a 2010 poll of 122 film professionals organized by the [[Golden Horse Film Festival and Awards|Taipei Golden Horse Film Festival]].<ref>
* {{cite web|title=100 Greatest Chinese-Language Films|url=http://100.goldenhorse.org.tw/|website=Taipei Golden Horse Film Festival|accessdate=20 January 2017}}
* {{cite web|title=100 Greatest Chinese-Language Films: Juries|url=http://100.goldenhorse.org.tw/juries/|website=Taipei Golden Horse Film Festival|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> It was also number 5, the highest ranked Taiwanese film, on the Hong Kong Film Awards' list of the [[Hong Kong Film Awards#Best 100 Chinese Motion Pictures|Best 100 Chinese Motion Pictures]], voted by 101 filmmakers, critics, and scholars.<ref name=HKFA/>

===Turkey===
{{See also|Cinema of Turkey}}
* ''[[Yol]]'' (1982) was voted the best Turkish film of all time in a 2016 poll of 383 experts organized by Turkish magazine ''Notos''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Türk Sineması'nda yüzyılın en iyi filmleri seçildi!|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/yuzyilin-en-iyi-turk-filmleri-secildi-yol-filmi-birinci-40046444|date=28 January 2016|website=Hürriyet|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> It was also selected as the best Turkish film in a 2003 poll undertaken by Ankara Sinema Derneği (Ankara Association for Cinema Culture) of people interested in cinema professionally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arsiv.ntvmsnbc.com/news/232930.asp|title='En İyi On Türk Filmi' belirlendi|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Arsiv.ntvmsnbc.com|language=Turkish|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>

===Ukraine===
{{See also|Cinema of Ukraine}}
