A '''middle-market newspaper''' is one that attempts to cater to readers who want [[Infotainment|some entertainment from their newspaper]] as well as the coverage of important news events. Middle-market status is the halfway point of a three-level continuum of journalistic seriousness; uppermarket or [[Quality press|"quality"]] newspapers generally cover hard news and down-market newspapers favour sensationalist stories. In the [[United Kingdom]], since the demise of ''[[Today (UK newspaper)|Today]]'' (1986–1995), the only national middle-market papers are the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and the ''[[Daily Express]]'', distinguishable by their black-top masthead (both use the easy-to-carry [[tabloid (paper size)|tabloid]] paper size), as opposed to the [[Tabloid journalism#Red tops|red-top]] mastheads of down-market [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]]s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JBSAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT36#v=onepage&q&f=false Read all about it!: a history of the British newspaper] Kevin Williams; Taylor & Francis, 2010; page 9</ref>

