{{Infobox person | name = Richard Korherr | image = Richard Korherr (1978).jpg | alt = Richard Korherr | caption = Korherr in 1978, at the age of 75 | birth_date = 30 October 1903 | birth_place = [[Regensburg]] | death_date = 24 November 1989 | death_place = [[Braunschweig]] | nationality = | occupation = [[Statistician]] | years_active = | known_for = The [[Korherr Report]] <ref name="HEART">{{cite web |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/holoprelude/korherr.html |title=The Richard Korherr Report |publisher=HolocaustResearchProject.org |author=Chris Webb, H.E.A.R.T |year=2009}}</ref> | notable_works = }}
Dr. '''Richard Korherr''' ([[Regensburg]], 30 October 1903 – 24 November 1989, [[Braunschweig]]) was a professional [[statistician]] in [[Nazi Germany]],<ref name="Mayr">{{cite book |author=Georg von Mayr |title=Allgemeines statistisches Archiv |volume=Band 74 |publisher=Vanderhoeck & Ruprecht |year=1990 |page=156 |url=https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&tbo=1&hl=en&q=%22Richard+Korherr%22+24.+November+1989 |via=Eingeschränkte Vorschau bei Google books.}}</ref> and chief inspector of the statistical bureau of the [[SS]] during World War II.<ref name=Korherr>{{cite web |author=Richard Korherr, Der Inspekteur für Statistik beim [[Reichsführer SS]] |year=1943 |url=http://www.ns-archiv.de/verfolgung/korherr/faksimile-lang/ |title=DIE ENDLÖSUNG DER EUROPÄISCHEN JUDENFRAGE |trans-title=The Final Solution to the Jewish Question |location=Berlin |publisher=NS-Archiv : Dokumente zum Nationalsozialismus : Korherr-Bericht, lange Fassung |accessdate=25 January 2016 |at=Facsimile of the Extant Text typed in German on 17 letter size pages}}</ref> Korherr eventually held the rank of [[SS-Sturmbannführer]].<ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm;jsessionid=3F9AECE1303DF7B9EBD3B06EEA7F6025.prod-worker1?method=showFullRecord&currentResultId=%22124375901%22%26any&currentPosition=0 Deutschen Nationalbibliothek - Dr. Richard Korherr, SS-Sturmbannführer, Chef der Statistik beim SS-Reichsführer Himmler über die Ermordung der Juden Europas / Institute of Documentation in Israel. Hrsg. von T. Friedman ]</ref>
Korherr received his doctorate in 1926 and worked for the {{Interlanguage link multi|Reich Statistical Office|de|3=Statistisches Reichsamt}} before [[Hitler's rise to power]]. He served as chairman<!--Vorsitzender--> of the Bavarian anti-separatist ''Reich und Heimat'' Committee in 1930-33, and became member of the Catholic [[Bavarian People's Party]]. On 1 January 1934 his department was taken over by the Bavarian Statistical Office, and he was transferred there.<ref name="Götz/angaben"/>
In 1935-40 Korherr was Director of the Statistical Office of the city of [[Würzburg]].<ref name="Götz/angaben">{{cite book |authors=Götz Aly, Karl Heinz Roth |title=Die restlose Erfassung: Volkszählen, Identifizieren, Aussondern im Nationalsozialismus |location=Frankfurt/M. |year=2000 |ISBN=3-596-14767-0 |publisher=Fischer Taschenbuch Verlag |pages=40–43}} ''(also in)'' {{cite book |author=Jutta Wietog |title=Volkszählungen unter dem Nationalsozialismus |location=Berlin |year=2002 |ISBN=3-428-10384-X |pages=209–237 |publisher=Duncker & Humblot |via=Google Books}}</ref> Following the [[invasion of Poland]] at the onset of World War II, on 9 December 1940 Himmler brought Korherr to [[Reichsführer-SS]] office, to study the progress of resettlement for him.<ref name="Götz/info"/> Korherr's incredible problems with the SS began only when the German advance on [[Eastern Front (World War II)|the Russian front]] had been halted, resulting in the most damning statistic often attributed to him.<ref name="Götz/info">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-GhQrKj9vQC&lpg=PA31&vq=Korherr%2BErlangen&pg=PA31#v=snippet&q=Korherr+Erlangen&f=false |pages=31–32 |title=The Nazi Census: Identification and Control in the Third Reich |authors=Götz Aly, Karl Heinz Roth |translator=Edwin Black, Assenka Oksiloff |publisher=Temple University Press |year=2004 |ISBN=1592132596 |via=Google Books}}</ref>
==Korherr Report== During World War II Korherr was commissioned by [[Heinrich Himmler]] to calculate the number of Jews in Europe subject to "special treatment" (''[[Sonderbehandlung]]'', an SS [[code name]] for [[mass murder]]) from 1937 to December 1942. Korherr completed his [[Korherr Report]] in January 1943 and handed it over to ''[[SS-Obersturmbannfuhrer]]'' Dr. [[Rudolf Brandt]] on the 23 March of that year. It was a 16-page document on the progress of [[the Holocaust]] as reflected in the dwindling numbers of Jews in Germany and [[German-occupied Europe]]. It included a seven-page supplement about the deportations in the first three months of 1943.<ref name="Hilberg">{{cite book |title=The Destruction of the European Jews |author=[[Raul Hilberg]] |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |year=2003 |ISBN=0300095929 |pages=1304–1305 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HinIpmliz2MC&lpg=PA1304&vq=Richard%2BKorherr&pg=PA1304#v=snippet&q=Richard+Korherr&f=false}}</ref> The report was released under the title ''Die Endlösung der Judenfrage'' ({{lang-en|the [[Final Solution]] to the Jewish Question}}). Korherr calculated that the number had fallen by 4 million, of whom 1,274,166 victims were delivered to camps for 'special treatment'. The exacting number of 1,274,166 Jews appeared in the [[Höfle Telegram|Telegram]] sent by ''[[SS-Sturmbannführer]]'' [[Hermann Höfle]] on 11 January 1943 suggesting that both of them used data collected by the German Transport Authority. Himmler returned the document to its author and demanded a more [[euphemism|innocuous word]] in place of the ''"[[Sonderbehandlung]]"'' to divert and obscure the crimes. Korherr replaced the phrase with ''"Durchgeschleust"'' suggesting that the quoted numbers of Jews had "passed through" the so-called [[Nazi concentration camps#Types of camps|''Durchgangslager'' (transit camps)]]. A summary of his report was delivered to Adolf Hitler by Brandt.<ref name="O'Neil">{{cite book |author=Dr. [[Robin O'Neil]] |title=The Rabka Four. Instruments of Genocide and Grand Larceny. A Warning from History |publisher=Spiderwize |date=June 27, 2011 |language=English |ISBN=1908128151 |page=xxvi |via=digitized copy made available by JewishGen, Inc. |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/Galicia3/gal000.html#f10r}}</ref>
In 1945-46 he was under so-called '[[Denazification|automatic arrest]]' as state functionary,{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} however he did not face the [[Nuremberg Trials]], because his Report was not revealed and he later claimed he never heard about the extermination before 1945.<ref>[[Ernst Klee]], ''Das Personenlexikon zum Dritten Reich'', Frankfurt 2005, {{ISBN|3-596-16048-0}}, p. 331.</ref>
Later Korherr worked at the [[Federal Ministry of Finance (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Finance]] in [[West Germany]]. He also lectured at the [[University of Erlangen-Nuremberg]] in 1959–62. Korherr died in the city of [[Braunschweig]], [[Lower Saxony]], on 24 November 1989 at the age of 86.
