hotos/mypixbox/2090276640/ |title=Flickr.com |publisher=Flickr.com |date=2007-12-05 |accessdate=2014-02-17}}</ref> * [[Penne, Abruzzo]], Italy, SPQP<ref name="Flickr.com"/> * [[Rotterdam]], the Netherlands, SPQR on a wallpainting in the {{ill|Rotterdam City Hall|nl|Stadhuis van Rotterdam}} * [[Siena]], Italy, SPQS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/rut/2688830684/ |title=Flickr.com |publisher=Flickr.com |date=2008-06-17 |accessdate=2014-02-17}}</ref> * [[Solothurn]], Switzerland, SPQS on the [[Solothurn Cathedral|Cathedral]] of [[Ursus of Solothurn|St Ursus]] and [[Viktor of Xanten|Victor]] * [[Terracina]], Italy, SPQT<ref>{{cite journal |author=O. A. W. Dilke and Margaret S. Dilke |date=October 1961 |title=Terracina and the Pomptine Marshes |journal=Greece & Rome |volume=II:8 |issue=2 |pages=172–178 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |issn=0017-3835 |oclc=51206579}}</ref> * [[Tivoli, Lazio]], Italy, SPQT<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tibursuperbum.it/eng/escursioni/passeggiate/Pomata.htm |title=Tibursuperbum.it |publisher=Tibursuperbum.it |date= |accessdate=2014-02-17}}</ref> * [[Valencia]], Spain, SPQV in several places and buildings, including the [[Llotja de la Seda|Silk Exchange]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/obra-visor/manual-del-viajero-y-guia-de-los-forasteros-en-valencia--0/html/feeb26d4-82b1-11df-acc7-002185ce6064_25.htm |title=Biblioteca Virtual Miguel de Cervantes |publisher=Cervantesvirtual.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-17}}</ref> and the [[University of Valencia]]<ref>http://farm4.staticflickr.com/3020/2927782582_9812c8d395_s.jpg</ref> Historic Building. * [[Verviers]], Belgium, SPQV on the Grand Theatre<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://www.bestofverviers.be/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=186:le-grand-theatre-de-verviers&catid=15:nos-lieux&Itemid=23 Bestofverviers.be]</ref> * [[Vienna]], Austria<ref name="fotw"/>
===Use by white supremacists=== Some members of [[White supremacy|white supremacist]] groups have been using the acronym SPQR on flags, on their person (such as [[Tattoo|tattoos]]) and other forms of identification.<ref name=Pharos1>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2018/07/27/scholars-respond-to-spqr-and-white-nationalism/|title=Scholars Respond to SPQR and White Nationalism|last=Angell (and others)|first=Ben|date=July 27, 2018|website=Pharos|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830171432/http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2018/07/27/scholars-respond-to-spqr-and-white-nationalism/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Pharos2>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2018/06/15/spqr-and-white-nationalism/|title=SPQR and White Nationalism|last=Angell (and others)|first=Ben|date=June 15, 2018|website=Pharos|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830171715/http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2018/06/15/spqr-and-white-nationalism/|archive-date=August 29, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=splc>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/08/12/flags-and-other-symbols-used-far-right-groups-charlottesville|title=Flags and Other Symbols Used By Far-Right Groups in Charlottesville|last=|first=|date=August 12, 2018|website=Southern Poverty Law Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830172934/https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/08/12/flags-and-other-symbols-used-far-right-groups-charlottesville|archive-date=August 29, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=August 29, 2018}}</ref> The movement's enthusiasm for other symbols of republican Rome, such as the axe and bundled rods known as [[fasces]], is documented, as well as their interest in some aspects of republican and imperial Rome.<ref name=Pharos3>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2017/12/11/american-fascist-manifesto-begins-with-the-roman-republic/|title=“American Fascist Manifesto” begins with the Roman Republic|last=Angell (and others)|first=Ben|date=December 11, 2017|website=Pharos|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830174800/http://pages.vassar.edu/pharos/2017/12/11/american-fascist-manifesto-begins-with-the-roman-republic/|archive-date=August 30, 2018|dead-url=|access-date=August 30, 2018}}</ref> That use was discussed on [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]]'s bulletin boards and was noticed at white supremacist demonstrations.<ref name=Pharos1/>
White supremacists tend to associate "SPQR" with the militaristic ethos of the Roman legions. There is no clear evidence that it appeared regularly on Roman military insignia and equipment, but SPQR was heavily used by [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]]'s [[Fascism|fascist]] regime.<ref name=Pharos2/>
While some white supremacists have adopted SPQR as a sort of badge, one should not confuse that usage with the large number of groups and individuals who also use it for other purposes.<ref name=Pharos1/>
===Popular culture=== {{Refimprove section|date=February 2018}} In the early twentieth century, the letters "SPQR" could sometimes be seen displayed on London market traders' stalls, meaning "Small Profits, Quick Returns".<ref name="FowlerFowler2011">{{cite book|last1=Fowler|first1=H. W.|author1-link=Henry Watson Fowler|last2=Fowler|first2=F. G.|author2-link=Francis George Fowler|last3=Crystal|first3=David|author3-link=David Crystal|title=The Concise Oxford Dictionary: The Classic First Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kbOcAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA748|year=2011|origyear=1911|publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-969612-3|page=748}}</ref>
''MPQN'', standing for ''Metallica Populusque [[Nîmes|Nimus]]'', appears on the cover of the [[Metallica]] live [[DVD]] ''[[Français Pour une Nuit]]'', which was recorded in the [[Arena of Nîmes]], a remodelled Roman amphiteatre.<ref>Cover of {{Discogs release|6751125|Français Pour Une Nuit - Live Aux Arènes De Nîmes 2009}}</ref>
The Italians have long used a different and humorous expansion of this acronym, "''Sono Pazzi Questi Romani''" (literally: "They're crazy, these Romans").<ref>See, e.g. {{cite book|title=Handbuch der theoretischen und praktischen Heraldik|location=Munich|year=1861|first=Otto Titan|last=von Hefner|page=106|url=https://archive.org/stream/handbuchdertheo00hefngoog#page/n122/mode/2up}}</ref> In the [[Asterix|Asterix and Obelix comics]], Obelix often uses the French translation of this phrase, "''Ils sont fous ces Romains''", and in the Italian editions, the original phrase is used.{{fact|date=March 2018}}
In the cover of the Spanish [[Mort & Phil]] comic album ''[[:es:La historia del dinero|La historia del dinero]]'',<ref name="Mortadelo">''La historia del dinero'', 1980, [[Editorial Bruguera]]/[[Bankunión]].</ref> Mort is carried on a [[litter]] as a Roman emperor, while his partner Phil holds a Roman standard topped by an umbrella with the ''[[titulus (inscription)|tituli]]'' SPOR and SI LLUEVE (a pun, since ''Es por si llueve'' means "Just in case it rains" in Spanish).{{fact|date=March 2018}}
In ''[[The Heroes of Olympus]]'' series by [[Rick Riordan]], SPQR is tattooed on the arms of members of the Roman Legion. In the film ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' the protagonist sports a similar tattoo.{{fact|date=March 2018}}
The [[SPQR series|''SPQR'' series]] is a collection of historical mystery stories by [[John Maddox Roberts]] set in the time of the Roman Republic.{{fact|date=March 2018}}
S.P.Q.R. Records was an American popular music record label, a subsidiary of Legrand Records, which flourished in the 1960s and included [[Gary U.S. Bonds]] among its artists. The label was founded by Frank Guida, who is believed to have adopted the name in allusion to his Italian origins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/about/spqr |title=Biography – S.P.Q.R. |work=45cat.com |accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>
In the Internet meme [[Polandball]], the Roman Empire is represented by SPQRball.{{fact|date=March 2018}}
The football team [[A.S. Roma]] wore special edition shirts with SPQR on the chest for their match against city rivals [[S.S. Lazio]] on 29 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma.com/en/news/2017/4/-spqr-adds-final-touch-to-special-derby-kit|title='SPQR' adds final touch to special derby kit|website=www.asroma.com}}</ref>
S.P.Q.R. is the fourth song on the critically acclaimed experimental rock album ''[[Deceit (album)|Deceit]]'' by [[This Heat]]. The song talks about atomic destruction and human morals using symbols of Rome.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/This-heat-spqr-lyrics|title=This Heat – S.P.Q.R.|publisher=}}</ref>
