==The Juvenile Englishman's Library== Paget as editor started a children's book collection, ''The Juvenile Englishman's Library'', in 1844. It was inspired in part by the success of [[Edgar Taylor (author)|Edgar Taylor]]'s English translations of ''[[Grimm's Fairy Tales]]''. The series ran to 21 titles. Later [[John Fuller Russell]] was editor.<ref name="Mitchell2012">{{cite book|author=Sally Mitchell|title=Victorian Britain (Routledge Revivals): An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yCNdsz5IlJwC&pg=PA284|accessdate=9 January 2013|date=6 August 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-66851-4|page=284}}</ref><ref>{{ODNBweb|id=11507|title=Gresley, William|first=S. A.|last=Skinner}}</ref> Volume 4, ''Popular Tales'' (1844), had translation of fairy tales by [[Friedrich de la Motte Fouqué]], [[Wilhelm Hauff]] and [[Karl Spindler (novelist)|Karl Spindler]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Gillian Lathey|title=The Role of Translators in Children's Literature: Invisible Storytellers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G85uSoUnrcwC&pg=PA83|accessdate=9 January 2013|date=23 June 2010|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-98952-7|page=83}}</ref> Four volumes were by [[John Mason Neale]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Neale, John Mason}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Ecclesiologist|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h4wQAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA14|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=1846|publisher=Cambridge Camden Society|pages=14–5}}</ref>
