{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Three-way-piece-no-3-vertebrae.JPG | painting_alignment = Front | image_size = 300px | title = Three-Piece No. 3: Vertebrae (Working Model) | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Henry Moore | year = 1968 | type = [[Bronze]] | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = 234 | imperial_unit = in | metric_unit = cm }} {{italic title|noerror|all=yes}} <!-- template after the infobox to prevent the display of error message --> '''''Three-Piece No. 3: Vertebrae (Working Model)''''' is a bronze sculpture by [[Henry Moore]].<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=KG0669200B169.45099&profile=ariall&uri=link=3100009~!1469772~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=Browse&menu=search&ri=3&source=~!siartinventories&term=Three+Piece+No.+3%3A+Vertebrae%2C&index=ALTIT "Three Piece No. 3: Vertebrae, (sculpture)"]. ''SIRIS''</ref> It was cast in 1968 as in edition of 8, along with an artist's copy which is now part of the [[Tate]] collection.<ref name=Tate>[http://www.tate.org.uk/art/research-publications/henry-moore/henry-moore-om-ch-working-model-for-three-piece-no3-vertebrae-r1171989 Tate: ''Working Model for Three Piece No. 3: Vertebrae'']</ref>
==Description== It is in the [[Nasher Sculpture Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hirshhorn.si.edu/visit/collection_object.asp?key=32&subkey=10404 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629171155/http://hirshhorn.si.edu/visit/collection_object.asp?key=32&subkey=10404 |archivedate=2011-06-29 |df= }}</ref> The sculpture refers to bones, which Moore collected.<ref>''A Garden for Art'', Valerie J. Fletcher, LOC # 97-61991, p.70</ref>
{{quote|Each of the forms, although different, has the same basic shape. Just as in a backbone which may be made up of twenty segments where each one is roughly like the others but not exactly the same…This is why I call these sculptures Vertebrae. The two or three forms are basically alike but are arranged to go with each other in different positions. The sculptor’s life is one of thinking, reacting, or making, expressing himself through form, through shape – for me the three-dimensional world is unending. <ref>{{cite web|title=Working Model for Three Piece No.3: Vertebrae 1968 (LH 579)|url=http://www.henry-moore.org/works-in-public/world/united-states-of-america/washington-dc/hirshhorn-museum-and-sculpture-garden/working-model-for-three-piece-no3-vertebrae-1968|publisher=Henry Moore Foundation|accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref>}}
